properties.name: Louisa Boren Park
properties.location_description: Start/End point at 15th Avenue E and E Garfield Street area
properties.sense_explanation: Honors one of Seattle's earliest citizens, home to historic trees, offers great views
properties.rhetorical_usage: hidden little treasure; great views; historic trees; honors one of Seattle's earliest citizens

properties.name: Former Leary House
properties.location_description: South on 10th Avenue E from E Blaine Street area
properties.sense_explanation: Grand building designed by Alfred Bodley for John and Eliza Leary, made of Tenino sandstone, later used by Red Cross and Episcopal Diocese

properties.name: Garry oak tree
properties.location_description: Corner where Belmont Place E and Belmont Avenue E intersect
properties.relative_distance: at the corner where the Belmonts intersect
properties.sense_explanation: Large and unusual tree, Washington's lone native oak, named by David Douglas
properties.rhetorical_usage: large and unusual tree; Washington's lone native oak; rare this far north

properties.name: Daughters of the American Revolution house
properties.location_description: East side of Harvard Avenue E on E Roy Street
properties.relative_distance: on the east side of Harvard Ave E on Roy St
properties.sense_explanation: Building built in 1925 as a copy of George Washington's home, Mount Vernon

properties.name: Former Woman's Century Club / Harvard Exit building
properties.location_description: Southeast corner of E Roy Street and Harvard Avenue E
properties.relative_distance: on the southeast corner of Roy and Harvard Ave
properties.sense_explanation: Club founded in 1891 for intellectual culture and social problems, built the present building, which later housed the Harvard Exit movie theater
properties.rhetorical_usage: former home of the Woman's Century Club; started by 10 women; served a need in the sordid atmosphere of a rapidly developing western city

properties.name: Arthur Loveless building
properties.location_description: North side of E Roy Street near the Harvard Exit building
properties.relative_distance: on your left as you walk east from the Harvard Exit
properties.sense_explanation: Two-story building built in 1931, described as "a little bit of England," centers on a private courtyard for artists' spaces
properties.rhetorical_usage: handsome two-story building; little bit of England; private courtyard

properties.name: Frederick Anhalt Apartments
properties.location_description: Roy Street area where it curves before the path
properties.relative_distance: between two brick apartment buildings as Roy St turns
properties.sense_explanation: Apartments developed in the late 1920s with French Norman-inspired elements and house-like features
properties.rhetorical_usage: elegant Capitol Hill apartments; French Norman-inspired elements

properties.name: Millionaire's Row / Granite hitching post
properties.location_description: 14th Avenue E area near E Roy Street
properties.relative_distance: turn left on 14th Ave E from E Mercer St (or arrive walking east on Roy St)
properties.sense_explanation: Area known for finest early 20th-century homes, includes a rare granite hitching post as a sign of early Seattle's equestrian history
properties.rhetorical_usage: long been known as 'Millionaire's Row'; finest early 20th-century homes; rare sign of early Seattleâ€”a granite hitching post

properties.name: James A. Moore Mansion
properties.location_description: Southwest corner of 14th Avenue E and E Aloha Street
properties.relative_distance: continue north on 14th Ave E one block to E Aloha St
properties.sense_explanation: Brick mansion built in 1903, was the home of Capitol Hill's developer James A. Moore
properties.rhetorical_usage: The brick mansion; home of Capitol Hill's developer
